                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The portion of the post that you are referring to I thought was necessary to the concept of instancing boss mobs.  Basically, when I read of this, I thought of two issues:
<br />

<br />
A) trivializing content
<br />
B) trivializing drops
<br />

<br />
Both of these need to be addressed.  As for A), this can be handled by putting some form of barrier to entry to the instanced zone, but, once the person/group/guild had done the work to get access, they WOULD be able to get to the mob.  Which leads to B), NOT trivializing the drop rate.
<br />

<br />
However, it also dawned on me that some of us are beating our heads up against a rare drop rate and doing so to a level of frustration that is just insane and really makes the game no fun.  That said, the drop rate has to remain at the same level of rarity.  Thus, though the boss mob might be reliably achievable, the rate of drop of the items once he is taken down needs to be monitored.  However, I'm arguing that for quest items, and the best example I alluded to are epic quest items, I feel the drop rate should be regulated such that the person who is working that quest, or is likely to work it, will not have to go through years, literally, of hunting for the drop.
<br />

<br />
Thus, the concept of flagging a character.  For example: an Enchanter ports up to Hate and his EoV flagged is incremented by 1.  S/he hunts in Hate and does NOT get the EoV drop so the flag remains.  S/he logs in Hate.  When s/he logs back into hate, the EoV flagged is incremented by 1 and is now a 2.  Each increment mildly increases the drop rate on mobs looted by the Flagged enchanter, or their group, until it's pretty much guaranteed to be seen... over what could be a LONG period of time depending on how we decide to allow said flags to affect the drop rate.  Once the EoV is looted by said Enchanter, their EoV flag is set to a -1 which is a way of saying that this Enchanters presence in the zone has NO effect on drop rate of EoV.  Yes this requires coding overhead both because the character now has a slew more flags to carry, and each quest has a similar amount of paperwork to track by character.  But, it's not insurmountable and it's reasonable.... and mostly it would stop parts of the game from literally becoming a hassle as opposed to being fun.  Note that it's important that the drop rate affect only those mobs looted by the Enchanter in question, their group or their raid.  I propose that in a raid setting with multiple characters of a given flag, the higher flag take effect.  Thus, in a raid with 2 SKs, one visiting Hate for the first time, the other for the 15th time, neither one with the drop, the one with 15 flags carries the weighting of the drop.
<br />

<br />
Now, how would this effect the drop rate of Koadics Robe of Heightened Focus?  I propose NO such flag for mere dropped items... this flag setup would ONLY be for queest items that require taking down a quest mob to gather then.  Thus Forsaken Revenants dropping of EoV would be affected... as would Phineous' dropping of the Staff for Mage epic, etc.  None of the other normal drop items would be affected this way.   The reason is that merely hunting drops, while being a bit frustrating, doesn't carry the added weight of seeing months of working on a particular quest frustrated night after night by a lack of drops.
<br />

<br />
The problem with this issue is exploits.  How do we stop a person from taking a sacrificial SK to Hate multiple times just to build up his flag and aid others in getting the drop?  The only mechanism I can come up with is fairly radical and that is to either reset the flag when an item of that nature is looted in a raid setting, OR to set all flags in the raid, group, or even zone, to the lowest flag currently in the raid, group or zone.  Ie: if the two SKs go on a raid, one has a flagging of 15 and the other a flagging of 1.  The SK epic item drops and the one with a 1 wins the roll or is "gifted" the drop.  The SK with 15 now has his flag set to 1 since his flag was instrumental in increasing the drop rate.
<br />

<br />
Food for thought... I'm sure we could debate and refine this idea for days.  The REAL intent is to maintain the sense of satisfaction of going after hard mobs/content while disallowing blocking content from anyone in the game.... as long as you work hard enough, get enough skill, to get to content, you can.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />GnarliAnna
<br />
E65.60/CT h+ 1.807khp 4.01km ft8 G++&lt;3 e++(+++) o++ T+++(+++++) L+ H++(+++) f++ g b@ c++ t+++ D++ X++</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
